text: I'm not going to go easy on this film. I love the original even with it's flaws. Because the original got the creep factor OH SO WELL down and was legit a feels movie. Sure towards the end there things got a bit funky. But it was still a pretty darn good movie in my opinion. I've wanted to rewatch it for a while. So i was so glad when i heard they where making a remake after how well the IT remake turned out. If they could work the same wonders with Pet Sematary i'm going to be so glad. not expecting something as good as the IT remake. But a film that irons out all the kinks and just improves what allready worked would be Amazing. So i'm putting my expectations high for this one. It might not be fare. But i'm not going to be fare. I'm expecting a great horror movie. That is something we sorely need more of. And the material they're working with here can make for one hell of a Horror movie. Stephen King is one of the best at his art. Sometimes not every aspect of his stories translate too well to the screen. But atleast it should make for a unique and exiting viewing experience even when you trim of the things that viewers just wouldn't be able to handle too well.

text: While I love the casting for Louis and Gage, I don't like the casting for Rachel and Ellie. From the book, I got the feeling that Rachel had sharper details, to match her sharp personality. Ellie, in the novel, was bratty and the definition of a snot-nosed kid, and this girl seems too old, and doesn't give me that vibe.  As far as Jud goes, while Lithgow is no Gwynne, I think he is as good as an actor as we could get. No one will be able to portray the character as well as Gwynne did, but I think Lithgow will do well (as long as he has that Maine accent)!  I also like the choice of Pascow, even though he is described as being white in the book; this guy gives me the eerie guide vibe, so I'm also happy with that decision!
